{# HERO: ticket — the hero as a kitchen dupe.

   A hard-left paper column with perforated top and bottom edges (a CSS mask,
   no image), the headline set as the order, tracked micro-labels, and the two
   CTAs as the actions at the foot. The rest of the viewport stays empty sand
   with a small corner mark.

   Serves counter-service, delis, sandwich shops, coffee bars — anywhere the
   ticket is the actual artefact of the transaction. It also inverts this
   template's own centring reflex, which is the specific thing the fold audit
   flagged.

   The headline uses .ticket-head rather than h1 styling alone so the ticket
   can hold a long order line without blowing the column; heroLoadIn() targets
   `h1` by tag, so the entrance still wires automatically.

   Meta row reuses `stamps`, which every site in this template already has, so
   no new config field is required. It is skipped entirely when absent. #}
<section class="hero-ticket">
  <div class="wrap hero-ticket-grid">
    <div class="ticket">
      <div class="eyebrow">{{ hero.eyebrow }}</div>
      <h1 class="ticket-head">{{ hero.headline }}</h1>
      <hr class="ticket-rule">
      <p class="sub">{{ hero.subhead }}</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="{{ hero.primary_cta.url }}">{{ hero.primary_cta.label }}</a>
        <a class="btn btn-outline" href="{{ hero.secondary_cta.url }}">{{ hero.secondary_cta.label }}</a>
      </div>
      {% if site.stamps and site.stamps.length %}
      <hr class="ticket-rule">
      <div class="ticket-meta">
        <span>{{ site.stamps[0] }}</span>
        {% if site.stamps.length > 1 %}<span>{{ site.stamps[1] }}</span>{% endif %}
      </div>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div class="hero-ticket-aside">
      <div class="hero-ticket-mark">
        <img src="{{ site.images.logo_mark }}" alt="" width="256" height="256" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
        <span class="htm-word">{{ site.business.name }}</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
